id="post-3500" class="post-3500 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-spin-da-news tag-flood tag-new-york tag-nyc"><h2 class="entry-title"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2012/11/02/good-designs-to-protect-against-flooding/" title="Permalink to Good Designs to Protect Against Flooding" rel="bookmark">Good Designs to Protect Against Flooding</a></h2><div
class="entry-meta"> <span
class="entry-date" title="2012/11/02 10:46 am"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2012/11/02/good-designs-to-protect-against-flooding/" title="Good Designs to Protect Against Flooding" rel="bookmark">2012/11/02 10:46 am</a></span><span
class="entry-meta-sep"> / </span><span
class="entry-author author vcard"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/author/administrator/" title="by Adam Clare" rel="author">Adam Clare</a></span></div><div
class="entry-content clearfix"><p>The damage of Hurricane Sandy is still being fully realized and we won&#8217;t know the full cost of the damage for a little while. What we can do for know is to look into ways to lessen the damage the next time an anthropogenically influenced storm hits the city. The Atlantic has put together some previously thought-out plans for preparing New York City for flooding from ideas that are used elsewhere in the world.</p><p>As ocean levels rise this will be a more pressing issue for New Yorkers and other cities on coasts.</p><p><iframe
width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/PxWZ7q7-4ws" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></p><p>Here&#8217;s what I think will be the easiest for NYC to implement, but I haven&#8217;t been there for years so I could be way off.</p><blockquote><p>2. Elevated infrastructure. There are very few buildings in the entire state of New York built at grade at elevations below sea level. But New York City has constructed one massive piece of infrastructure below that threshold: the subway system. As we saw this week, flooding can devastate an underground network of tunnels, train platforms and corridors. So how do you keep more of that water out? For one thing, elevating subway entrances would help. Bangkok, another low-lying city susceptible to rising tides, has built precisely these kinds of subway entrances. They’re raised a meter off the ground and include built-in floodgates.</p></blockquote><p><a
href="http://www.theatlanticcities.com/technology/2012/10/5-ideas-could-have-prevented-flooding-new-york/3754/">See the rest of the ideas here.</a></p><div
class='sharedaddy sd-block sd-like jetpack-likes-widget-wrapper jetpack-likes-widget-unloaded' id='like-post-wrapper-1111807-3500-5384310e984b7' data-src='//widgets.wp.com/likes/#blog_id=1111807&amp;post_id=3500&amp;origin=www.thingsaregood.com&amp;obj_id=1111807-3500-5384310e984b7' data-name='like-post-frame-1111807-3500-5384310e984b7'><h3 class='sd-title'>Like this:</h3><div
class='likes-widget-placeholder post-likes-widget-placeholder' style='height:55px'><span
